1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:06,616
Job hunting means the same work over and over. Finding the postings. Reading them properly.

2
00:00:06,866 --> 00:00:12,314
Working out whether you're actually a fit. DevJobInfo does that part for you.

3
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:16,408
Everything lands on one dashboard.

4
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:22,952
How many jobs came in, how well they match you, and how many applications you've sent this week.

5
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:32,104
Underneath, your pipeline by stage — saved, applied, interviewing, and the ones that have gone quiet.

6
00:00:32,354 --> 00:00:38,306
Plus how your match scores are spread, so you can see whether you're aiming at the right roles.

7
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:43,704
It all rests on your profile. This is what every job gets scored against.

8
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:51,600
Drop in your CV and it fills itself in — skills, experience, education, the lot.

9
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:58,312
From there you can adjust anything. The more accurate this is, the more honest the scoring gets.

10
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:07,608
Search five job boards at once — one query instead of five tabs.

11
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:15,704
Or paste a URL straight in, and it'll pull the posting apart for you.

12
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:24,416
Postings in any language work as they are. A Danish job stays in Danish — nothing gets translated behind your back.

13
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:32,568
Every job comes back scored from nought to a hundred against your profile.

14
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:39,264
When a posting is too thin to judge fairly, it caps the score instead of pretending otherwise.

15
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:43,312
Open any job for the full reasoning.

16
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:48,056
Which skills matched, which are missing, and why it landed there.

17
00:01:49,200 --> 00:01:55,800
Experience and seniority score separately, so a skills match can't mask a role that's too junior.

18
00:01:56,050 --> 00:02:00,418
From here, a cover letter — written from your actual history.

19
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:05,800
In the language of the posting, so a Danish job gets a Danish letter.

20
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:18,648
And nothing invented. No companies you didn't work for, no projects you didn't build. Only what's in your profile.

21
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:27,408
Then a resume tailored to this specific role.

22
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:37,056
Same career, reordered around what this employer actually asked for — the relevant work first, the rest still there.

23
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:45,216
Both download as PDFs, ready to send.

24
00:02:51,742 --> 00:02:56,398
Find the jobs. Research the companies. Land the role.

25
00:02:56,648 --> 00:03:00,200
DevJobInfo — devjob.info
